{
  "texts": [
    "Using a localizedorbital representation |αk⟩ = R e ik•R |αR⟩, with orbital index α and lattice vector R, the position matrix elements can be decomposed into on-site and intersite contributions.",
    "For the z component one can writer z mnk = r z,on nnk + r z,inter mnk,(5)where the on-site part depends only on the z-coordinates of the orbital centers d(α) z, r z,on mnk = α c (m) * αk c (n) αk d (α) z,(6)and r z,inter mnk collects all remaining intersite terms involving overlaps ⟨α0|r z |α ′ R⟩ with either R ̸ = 0 or α ̸ = α ′.",
    "In minimal tight-binding models built from point-like planar orbitals, r z,inter mnk is often neglected and d (α) z may be identical for all orbitals in a given layer, so the static field effectively enters only as a layer-resolved on-site potential.",
    "In contrast, Wannier Hamiltonians constructed from ab initio calculations naturally generate finite intersite dipole matrix elements [48,49,51,56], allowing the static field to modify both orbital hybridization and band dispersion.",
    "This distinction is crucial in planar systems or in centrosymmetric multilayers, where purely on-site models can artificially suppress the coupling to the static field."
  ]
}